President Biden spoke at the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma, Alabama, emphasizing the importance of voting rights and the need to protect democracy. He acknowledged the historical significance of the bridge and the sacrifices made by civil rights activists who fought for equal voting rights. President Biden criticized the efforts to restrict voting access, particularly targeting communities of color, and called for the passage of the John Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act and the Freedom to Vote Act. He also discussed his administration's efforts to address other issues, such as infrastructure, affordable housing, healthcare, and economic inequality. President Biden emphasized the need to build an economy that benefits all Americans and to ensure that everyone has access to opportunities and resources. He highlighted the progress made so far, including the passage of the American Rescue Plan and the reduction of prescription drug prices. President Biden called for unity and urged Americans to continue the fight for justice, equality, and a better future for all.